attributes.title: Physical stock take
attributes.description:

attributes.title: Bread Damages analysis
attributes.description:
·       A review of damages arising from production and markets for the period 15 March 2025 to 23 April 2025 was done to determine if the damage levels were within the set limits of 0.2% of total production and 0.5% of total sales.

·       The findings were as follows:

ü  Production damages were 0.23% of the total production which was above the set standard of 0.2% and had a cost implication of KES 11,953.11

ü  Market damages were 0.52% of the total sales, which was above the 0.5% allowed limit and had a cost implication of KES 6,165.37.

Table 4:Production Damages.

NB: The analysis was exclusive of 312 pcs of oven damages.

Table 5:Market Damages.
attributes.recommendation: Branch management to enhance controls to ensure proper flow of production process to ensure bread quality is achieved.
attributes.effect: Production and market damages exceeded the set damage limits, implying inadequate and inefficient controls for damages management.

value: Proper follow-up on flow of production process to be done to minimize excess damages.

·       Excess market returns were due to deformities to improper bread handling. We will put more controls.For production damages we will enhance bread quality by ensuring correct Standard production procedures are followed.
In the prior audit dated 10th March 2025, it was noted that production damages were 0.25% of the production and market damages stood at 0.53% of the total sales.

attributes.title: Production efficiency
attributes.description:
·       Production efficiency was done for a period of 40 days from 15 March 2025-23 April 2025 to determine if production workers were achieving their set efficiency of 4.3 bags per production worker.

·       It was noted that the average production efficiency was at 4.28 bags per production worker, which was below the set standard of 4.3, excess workers who were hired were hired were 25.

·       The table below illustrates the findings.

Table 7:Production efficiency.
attributes.recommendation: Branch management to ensure optimal allocation of employees to the production section.
attributes.effect: Production workers did not achieve efficiency hence the company incurred an extra cost of Kshs 27,165 for hiring extra 25 workers.

value: This was contributed to by breakdowns and cases of employees falling sick in the middle of the shift. We will do a follow to ensure improvements.
This was contributed to by breakdowns and cases of employees falling sick in the middle of the shift. We will do a follow to ensure improvements.
The previous audit report dated 10th March 2025 indicated a production efficiency of 4.28 bags per production worker.

attributes.description:

·       The analysis covered a period of 40 days from 15 March 2025-23 April 2025, which showed that packing efficiency stood at 91.14 crates which was below the standard,32 extra workers were hired with a cost implication of Kshs 29,184 set as detailed below:

Table 8:Packing efficiency.
attributes.recommendation: The branch management to ensure optimal allocation of packers based on the set standards.
attributes.effect: The branch did not attain the set slicing efficiency implying extra cost of KES 29,184 for hiring extra 32 slicers.

value: We will push slicers to ensure they are achieving efficiency.
This was contributed by breakdowns in slicing machine but the issue has been resolved and cases of employees falling sick in the middle of the shift.We will do a follow to ensure improvements

attributes.title: Mixing Chart analysis
attributes.description:
·       An analysis of both the mixing chart and mixing chart summaries for the period 15March 2025-23 April 2025 was done to determine if the raw materials’ consumption were as per the set BOM and if the set yield and quality standards were achieved for production.

·       The following was noted:

ü  Average yield was 191.05 loaves per bag

ü  Average production was 98.38 bags equivalent to 79.33% of the set target of 124 bags.

ü  Utto units’ consumption to bags of flour ratio was 1:1

ü   2,022 cases of remixes were observed for the reviewed audit period as detailed in the table below:

Table 9:Mixing Chart analysis.
attributes.recommendation: ·       The branch management to minimize remix cases by adhering to the set procedures.Sales team to put more effort to onboard more customers to ensure Branch capacity is fully utilized
attributes.effect: The high number of remixes imply lapses in following the set procedures in the production process. Branch is not fully utilized by 20.67% hence there is need for improving sales.

value: ·       Target achievement in March was due to frequent machine breakdowns MBN-246 and 248, had we scale down for repairs, Bread balance due to low sales hence production scaled down. Remixes were contributed by power outage and mixer breakdowns and the issue has been resolved.

Target not achieved in March was due to frequent machine breakdowns MBN-246 and 248, had we scale down for repairs, Bread balance due to low sales hence production scaled down.Remixes were contributed by power outage and mixer breakdowns and, but issue has been resolved.

attributes.title: Debtors analysis
attributes.description:
·       A review of debtors balances as at 24 April 2025 was done to determine if the branch had any cases of long outstanding balances that could pose risks of bad debts and to determine if there were customers issued bread above their security deposit and extra cent limits.

·       A total debtors worth Kshs1,146,986.20 were noted exclusive of overpayments which were secured by security deposits and extra cent as detailed below :

·       It was also noted that overpayments were worth Kshs 159,623.90 out of which there were those that were due to errors/wrong postings as detailed below:

·       It was also noted that the branch customers pay through several accounts’ others pay via main account, donholm equitel, South C account, Ngara, Kirinyaga, Eastleigh Other cash which complicates reconciliation process and make it harder to accurately track and allocate payments.

·       It was also noted that there was a new customer for pilot Route who issued bread above the Security deposit of Ksh 2,000 which has led to a debt of Ksh 161,666 as at 24 April 2025.
attributes.recommendation:
·       Branch management to enhance debt collection procedures to minimize significant debtors’ balances.

·       Posting of customer payments should be made on time to avoid cases of customers claiming they have paid and the same has not been posted .We also recommend the branch to have one payment account/method for easy reconciliation /verification and allocation of payments
attributes.effect: The significant debtors’ balances is an indication of weak debt collection controls and timely reconciliation of customer payments leading to errors.
